{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nEpic 3156 required a **visual-editor UX** for authoring project criteria (story 6e31). That UX is\nBROKEN for the primary case — authoring a NET-NEW criterion — so the deliverable's user experience\nfails a round trip:\n\n- A project criterion MUST be `project.<name>`-prefixed (the overlay namespace that guarantees a\n  project criterion can never rebind a built-in — ef7e/ADR 0015).\n- Its rubric is a prompt stored at `.rebar/prompts/plan-review-<id>.md`, and `get_prompt` /\n  `create_prompt` derive that filename from the criterion id as `plan-review-<id>`.\n- But `prompt_library._validate_id` → `prompt_authoring._valid_id` enforces `[A-Za-z0-9][A-Za-z0-9-]*`\n  — **no `.`** (a filename-safety rule: a `.` would let an id masquerade as a `<id>.<variant>.md`\n  overlay and enables traversal). So `plan-review-project.foo` is rejected at author time, AND\n  `.rebar/prompts/` would mis-read a dotted stem as a variant overlay.\n\nNet effect: the editor can RE-TUNE a built-in (id `F1`) but CANNOT author a net-new `project.<name>`\ncriterion end-to-end — the exact thing project-supplied criteria exist for. 6e31 currently\nvalidate-then-rollback-rejects the attempt with a clean 400, so it never persists a broken overlay,\nbut the UX still dead-ends. This must be remediated for the editor UX to actually work.\n\n## What — decouple the logical id from the physical filename (the Semgrep/npm/Python pattern)\n\nPopular, actively-maintained tools NEVER force a namespaced logical id to also be a raw filename;\nthey decouple via ONE deterministic mapping:\n- **Semgrep**: the dotted rule `id` is a metadata field, decoupled from the file name.\n- **npm**: `@scope/name` → a deterministic path `node_modules/@scope/name/`.\n- **Python**: `a.b.c` → `a/b/c.py` (dots → path separators).\n\nApply the same here. The criterion id stays `project.<name>` (dotted) EVERYWHERE it matters\n(overlay key, `activate`, routing, no-rebind collision check, the `.`→`_` workflow-output-key\nsanitization). Only the RUBRIC's physical storage is decoupled, via a SINGLE canonical function:\n\n- Add `criterion_prompt_id(criterion_id) -> str` (one source of truth): a built-in `<id>` →\n  `plan-review-<id>` (unchanged); a `project.<name>` → `plan-review-project-<name>` (`.`→`-`), a\n  filesystem-safe, `_valid_id`-valid prompt id. Injective because a project name is constrained to\n  a DOT-FREE charset (exactly one namespace dot) — validate this in `_validate_routing_entry` /\n  the namespace check so `project.a-b` and any dotted variant can never collide.\n- Route BOTH sides through it so they can never diverge:\n  - descriptor resolution: `criteria.model.build_descriptor` / `plan_review.registry` resolve a\n    project criterion's rubric via `get_prompt(criterion_prompt_id(cid), repo_root=...)` (not the\n    raw `plan-review-<cid>`);\n  - editor authoring: `criterion_preview.author_criterion_overlay` writes the rubric via\n    `create_prompt(criterion_prompt_id(cid), ...)` (now a valid id → passes `_valid_id`), then the\n    atomic overlay routing+activate write keyed by the dotted `project.<name>` id.\n- `enumerate_library` / `_user_prompt_ids`: a `plan-review-project-<name>.md` stem has no `.`, so it\n  is enumerated normally (no variant-overlay mis-read). No change needed beyond using the sanitized\n  filename.\n\n## Scope\n\n- Files: `src/rebar/llm/criteria/model.py` (or a small shared `ids.py`) — `criterion_prompt_id`;\n  `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/registry.py` + `src/rebar/llm/criteria/model.py` (descriptor rubric\n  resolution); `src/rebar/llm/workflow/criterion_preview.py` (authoring writes via the mapping);\n  `src/rebar/llm/criteria/overlay.py` or `_validate_routing_entry` (constrain project name to\n  dot-free); the editor UI (`editor_assets/src/rebarProvider.jsx`) so the authoring form derives +\n  shows the resulting criterion id.\n- **No back-compat burden (just-shipped feature):** project criteria shipped in ef7e days ago with\n  no external data/users, so backward compatibility is NOT a requirement — the sanitized form is\n  simply THE form. One clean code path (no dotted-`get_prompt` fallback). The ef7e/overlay TEST\n  FIXTURES that hand-place a dotted `plan-review-project.no_print.md` are just rewritten to the\n  sanitized `project.no-print` → `plan-review-project-no-print.md` — a free edit, not a migration.\n  Built-in prompt-id resolution is unchanged only because there is no reason to touch it, not for\n  compat.\n- **Project-name charset (RESOLVED):** a project criterion name follows the SAME rule as any prompt\n  id — `[A-Za-z0-9][A-Za-z0-9-]*` (alnum + dash; NO dots, NO underscores) — with exactly ONE\n  namespace dot in the full id (`project.<name>`). This makes `criterion_prompt_id` a total,\n  injective, filesystem-safe map (`.`→`-` on the single namespace dot). A name containing `.` or\n  `_` (or otherwise not matching the charset) is a LOCATED error at overlay load.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] A single canonical `criterion_prompt_id(criterion_id)` maps `project.<name>` →\n      `plan-review-project-<name>` (filesystem-safe, passes `_valid_id`) and a built-in `<id>` →\n      `plan-review-<id>` (unchanged); it is the ONLY id→prompt-filename derivation, used by BOTH\n      descriptor resolution and editor authoring.\n- [ ] A net-new `project.<name>` criterion can be authored end-to-end via the editor\n      (`create_prompt` no longer rejects it) AND then loaded/run by the gate (`load_criteria`\n      resolves its rubric) — a test proves the full author→activate→load→run round trip.\n- [ ] Project names are constrained to a dot-free charset (one namespace dot) so the id→prompt-id\n      map is injective; a name with a `.` is a located error.\n- [ ] `criterion_prompt_id` is total + injective: a built-in `<id>` → `plan-review-<id>` and a\n      `project.<name>` → ONLY `plan-review-project-<name>` (no dotted fallback); a dotted/underscored\n      project name is a located error. (Back-compat is not a requirement — one clean path.)\n- [ ] The editor authoring form surfaces the resulting criterion id (`project.<name>`) so the user\n      sees what will be created; a net-new author no longer dead-ends at a 400.\n\n\n## The dotted criterion id flows through explicitly (remediation, run 2)\n\nThe mapping `criterion_prompt_id` is ONE-WAY (`project.foo` → `plan-review-project-foo`); it is NOT\nreversible (a name may contain dashes, so `plan-review-project-foo-bar` can't be un-split to a unique\ndotted id). Therefore the DOTTED criterion id (`project.foo`) is the primary key and must be carried\nexplicitly — never reverse-derived from the sanitized prompt id:\n- The editor authoring form has an explicit **criterion-id field** whose value IS the dotted id\n  (`project.<name>`); the `/library/create` POST body carries BOTH `id` = the dotted criterion id AND\n  the `routing` object. (Today `_library_create` strips `plan-review-` off the prompt id to recover\n  `cid` — that path only works for built-ins; for a project criterion the dotted id comes from the\n  form field, not from un-stripping.)\n- `author_criterion_overlay(criterion_id, routing, *, repo_root)` takes the DOTTED `criterion_id` as\n  its primary argument. It computes `prompt_id = criterion_prompt_id(criterion_id)` for the\n  `create_prompt(prompt_id, rubric)` write, and keys the overlay `plan_review[criterion_id]` +\n  `activate` entries by the DOTTED id. So the sanitized prompt filename is derived once, forward-only;\n  the dotted id is authoritative for the overlay + activation.\n- `write_criterion_overlay(repo_root, criterion_id, routing)` likewise keys by the dotted id.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria (remediation addition, run 2)\n\n- [ ] The dotted criterion id (`project.<name>`) is passed EXPLICITLY through authoring (the editor\n      form's id field → `/library/create` body → `author_criterion_overlay(criterion_id=...)`), never\n      reverse-derived from the sanitized prompt id; the overlay entry + `activate` are keyed by the\n      dotted id while the rubric is written at `criterion_prompt_id(criterion_id)`.\n\n\n## Call-site responsibility (remediation, run 3 — the single wiring table)\n\nExactly one site applies `criterion_prompt_id`; every site's job is pinned:\n\n1. **Editor form** (`rebarProvider.jsx`): the id field's value IS the dotted criterion id\n   (`project.<name>`). POST `/library/create` body = `{id: \"project.<name>\", kind: \"criterion\",\n   body: <rubric md>, routing: {...}}`.\n2. **`editor._library_create`** (the orchestrator): for `kind == \"criterion\"` with a `routing`, it\n   (a) computes `prompt_id = criteria.ids.criterion_prompt_id(id)`; (b) calls\n   `create_prompt(prompt_id, body, repo_root=...)` — THIS is the ONE place `criterion_prompt_id` is\n   applied before `create_prompt`, so the sanitized (valid) id reaches the write path; (c) calls\n   `write_criterion_overlay(repo_root, criterion_id=id, routing)` keyed by the DOTTED id (routing +\n   `activate`). Order is prompt-first (a failed overlay leaves an inactive, harmless prompt), and the\n   overlay write is the existing atomic validate-then-rollback.\n3. **`author_criterion_overlay`** is RENAMED/refocused to take the dotted `criterion_id` (not a\n   prompt id) — it no longer strips `plan-review-` to recover the id (that path only worked for\n   built-ins and can't recover a dotted id from the sanitized one). It delegates the routing+activate\n   write to `write_criterion_overlay(repo_root, criterion_id, routing)`.\n4. **Descriptor resolution** (`plan_review/registry._get_prompt` at registry.py:236 + the shared\n   `criteria.model.build_descriptor` prompt path): resolve a criterion's rubric via\n   `get_prompt(criterion_prompt_id(criterion_id), repo_root=...)` instead of the raw\n   `f\"plan-review-{cid}\"` — so a `project.<name>` reads `plan-review-project-<name>.md`.\n5. **`criterion_prompt_id`** lives in a new tiny `src/rebar/llm/criteria/ids.py` (the single source),\n   imported by both the editor authoring path and the descriptor path so they can never diverge.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria (remediation addition, run 3)\n\n- [ ] `criterion_prompt_id` is applied at exactly ONE pre-`create_prompt` site\n      (`editor._library_create` for authoring) and at the descriptor-resolution site\n      (`registry._get_prompt` / `build_descriptor`); a test authors `project.<name>` via\n      `/library/create` and asserts the rubric lands at `.rebar/prompts/plan-review-project-<name>.md`\n      AND `load_criteria` resolves it.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782907902535016001,"uuid":"8b4504cc-3050-4ae4-bb40-f9cd21e4d4a1"}